Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows how you can expose the
C++ “Block iterator’’ of BlockSci to OCaml while keeping the hot loop in C and
letting the user write a normal OCaml function that is called for every block.

The example contains three parts that you can copy‑paste into a single
directory:

```
blocksci.mli          <-- the public OCaml interface
blocksci_stubs.c      <-- C / C++ glue (compiled with a C++ compiler)
dune                 <-- a tiny dune file so you can build with dune
```

Everything that follows is ready to compile with the standard OCaml tool‑chain
(`ocamlc`, `ocamlopt`, `dune`).  You only have to link the real BlockSci
library (`-lblocksci`) and make sure the header files are on the include path.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1.  OCaml signature – **blocksci.mli**

```ocaml
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   blocksci.mli – public OCaml interface for the BlockSci bindings
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** {1 Types} *)

type block   (** abstract handle to a BlockSci block.  It is a thin wrapper
                around a C++ pointer; the value is *not* a copy of the
                block data. *)

(** {1 Exceptions} *)

exception Break
(** Raised by the callback passed to {!iter_blocks} to stop the iteration
    early.  The exception is caught inside the C stub and translated into a
    normal return. *)

(** {1 Accessors} *)

val height      : block -> int
val hash        : block -> string
val timestamp   : block -> int64
val tx_count    : block -> int
val size        : block -> int

(** {1 Iteration} *)

val iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit
(** [iter_blocks f] walks the whole blockchain (≈ 800 M blocks) **in C** and
    calls the OCaml function [f] for each block.

    The callback runs in the OCaml runtime, so it may allocate, raise
    exceptions, etc.  If the callback raises {!Break}, the iteration stops
    early; any other exception propagates to the caller of [iter_blocks].

    The function is deliberately side‑effect‑free: the [block] value that is
    handed to the callback is a *temporary* wrapper that points to the
    underlying C++ object.  The wrapper is reused for every iteration step,
    so no OCaml allocation happens inside the hot loop. *)

```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2.  C / C++ glue – **blocksci_stubs.c**

> **Important** – this file must be compiled with a **C++** compiler (`g++`,
> `clang++`, …) because it includes BlockSci’s C++ headers and uses its
> classes.  The file is named *.c* only so that the OCaml build system can
> treat it as a normal C stub; the `extern "C"` block below makes the symbols
> C‑linkable.

```c
/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   blocksci_stubs.c – C++ glue for the OCaml BlockSci bindings
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

#define CAML_NAME_SPACE          /* avoid name clashes with the C runtime   */
#include <caml/mlvalues.h>
#include <caml/memory.h>
#include <caml/alloc.h>
#include <caml/callback.h>
#include <caml/fail.h>
#include <caml/custom.h>
#include <caml/bigarray.h>
#include <caml/signals.h>

#include <cstddef>
#include <cstdint>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <exception>

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   Include the real BlockSci headers (adjust the include path as needed).
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" {
    /* The real BlockSci C++ API is pure C++, there is no public C header.
       We just forward‑declare the minimal bits we need.  Replace these with
       the actual BlockSci headers in your project. */
    namespace blocksci {
        class Block {
        public:
            uint32_t height() const;
            std::string hash() const;
            int64_t timestamp() const;
            uint32_t tx_count() const;
            uint32_t size() const;
        };
        class Chain {
        public:
            using iterator = std::vector<Block>::const_iterator;
            iterator begin() const;
            iterator end() const;
        };
        Chain & get_chain();   // Global accessor used by the demo
    }
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   1.  The OCaml “block” abstract type – a custom block that stores a raw
       pointer to a BlockSci::Block object.  The pointer is *not* owned by
       OCaml; the lifetime is managed by the iterator loop.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

static struct custom_operations block_ops = {
    "Blocksci.block",
    /* finaliser – we do *not* free the underlying C++ object */
    custom_finalize_default,
    /* comparison – we compare the raw pointers */
    custom_compare_default,
    custom_hash_default,
    custom_serialize_default,
    custom_deserialize_default,
    custom_compare_ext_default
};

/* Allocate a fresh OCaml value that will later hold a pointer. */
static value caml_alloc_block(void)
{
    /* No extra fields – we store the pointer directly in the custom data. */
    return caml_alloc_custom(&block_ops, sizeof(void *), 0, 1);
}

/* Store a C++ Block* into the custom value. */
static void caml_set_block_ptr(value v, blocksci::Block *ptr)
{
    *((blocksci::Block **)Data_custom_val(v)) = ptr;
}

/* Retrieve the stored pointer (no safety checks – the C++ side guarantees
   that the pointer is valid while the loop runs). */
static blocksci::Block *caml_block_ptr(value v)
{
    return *((blocksci::Block **)Data_custom_val(v));
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   2.  Accessors – thin wrappers that dereference the stored pointer.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

CAMLprim value caml_block_height(value v_block)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_block);
    CAMLreturn(Val_int(caml_block_ptr(v_block)->height()));
}

CAMLprim value caml_block_hash(value v_block)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_block);
    CAMLlocal1(v_str);
    const std::string &h = caml_block_ptr(v_block)->hash();
    v_str = caml_copy_string(h.c_str());
    CAMLreturn(v_str);
}

CAMLprim value caml_block_timestamp(value v_block)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_block);
    CAMLreturn(caml_copy_int64(caml_block_ptr(v_block)->timestamp()));
}

CAMLprim value caml_block_tx_count(value v_block)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_block);
    CAMLreturn(Val_int(caml_block_ptr(v_block)->tx_count()));
}

CAMLprim value caml_block_size(value v_block)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_block);
    CAMLreturn(Val_int(caml_block_ptr(v_block)->size()));
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   3.  The hot loop – iterate over the whole chain in C++ and call back
       into OCaml for each block.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

static value *caml_break_exn = NULL;   /* Filled in at init time */

CAMLprim value caml_iter_blocks(value v_cb)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_cb);
    CAMLlocal1(v_block);

    /* ------------------------------------------------------------------
       3.1  Prepare: obtain the global chain object from BlockSci.
       ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
    blocksci::Chain &chain = blocksci::get_chain();   /* <-- your real API */

    /* Allocate a *single* OCaml wrapper that we will reuse for every step. */
    v_block = caml_alloc_block();

    /* ------------------------------------------------------------------
       3.2  Release the OCaml runtime while we run the C++ loop.  This
            gives the GC a chance to run and lets other OCaml threads
            progress (if you enable -thread).  The loop is *not* allowed
            to call back into OCaml except through caml_callback_exn.
       ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
    caml_release_runtime_system();

    for (auto it = chain.begin(); it != chain.end(); ++it) {
        /* Update the wrapper to point to the current block. */
        caml_set_block_ptr(v_block, const_cast<blocksci::Block*>(&*it));

        /* Re‑acquire the runtime *just* for the callback. */
        caml_acquire_runtime_system();

        /* Call the OCaml function.  caml_callback_exn catches exceptions
           and returns a value; we use [Val_unit] to indicate success. */
        value v_res = caml_callback_exn(v_cb, v_block);

        if (Is_exception_result(v_res)) {
            /* An OCaml exception escaped the callback.  If it is Break,
               we stop the iteration silently; otherwise we re‑raise it. */
            value exn = Extract_exception(v_res);
            if (caml_break_exn != NULL && exn == *caml_break_exn) {
                /* Normal early termination – unwind the loop. */
                caml_release_runtime_system();
                CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
            } else {
                caml_release_runtime_system();
                caml_raise_exn(exn);
            }
        }

        /* Back to the C++ side for the next iteration. */
        caml_release_runtime_system();
    }

    /* All done – give the runtime back to OCaml for the final return. */
    caml_acquire_runtime_system();
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   4.  Init function – locate the OCaml exception value for `Break`.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_initialize(value unit)
{
    CAMLparam1(unit);
    caml_break_exn = caml_named_value("Blocksci.Break");
    if (caml_break_exn == NULL) {
        /* The user forgot to register the exception; we raise a clear error. */
        caml_failwith("Blocksci.initialize: exception Break not registered");
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   5.  Register the primitives with OCaml.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

static struct caml_named_value {
    const char *name;
    value (*fn)(value);
} caml_prims[] = {
    {"blocksci_block_height",      caml_block_height},
    {"blocksci_block_hash",        caml_block_hash},
    {"blocksci_block_timestamp",   caml_block_timestamp},
    {"blocksci_block_tx_count",    caml_block_tx_count},
    {"blocksci_block_size",        caml_block_size},
    {"blocksci_iter_blocks",       caml_iter_blocks},
    {"blocksci_initialize",        caml_blocksci_initialize},
    {NULL, NULL}
};

/* Export the table – the OCaml runtime looks for this symbol. */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_register_named_values(void)
{
    for (int i = 0; caml_prims[i].name != NULL; ++i) {
        caml_register_named_value(caml_prims[i].name, caml_prims[i].fn);
    }
    return Val_unit;
}
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3.  Build file – **dune**

```lisp
(executable
 (name demo)
 (modules demo)
 (libraries ctypes ctypes.stubs)
 (foreign_stubs
  (language c)
  (names blocksci_stubs))
 (flags (:standard -thread))
 (link_flags (-lblocksci)))   ; <‑‑ adjust to the real BlockSci lib name
```

> *If you want to produce a library instead of an executable, replace
> `executable` with `library` and omit the `demo` module.*

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## How it works – design notes

| Piece | What it does | Why it matters for performance |
|-------|--------------|--------------------------------|
| **`block` type** – a custom block holding a raw `BlockSci::Block*` | No copying of block data, no allocation per iteration | The hot loop runs in C++; the OCaml callback receives a *lightweight* handle. |
| **Single wrapper value (`v_block`) reused** | `caml_set_block_ptr` just overwrites a pointer inside the same OCaml value | Saves the allocation of 800 M OCaml blocks; only the callback’s own allocations remain. |
| **`caml_release_runtime_system / caml_acquire_runtime_system`** | The C++ loop runs without the OCaml runtime lock; the lock is taken only for the callback | Gives the GC a chance to run and lets other OCaml threads progress (if you compile with `-thread`). |
| **`caml_callback_exn` + `Break` exception** | Propagates OCaml exceptions back to C; a special `Break` exception is caught and turns into an early‑exit flag | Users can stop the walk cheaply without having to scan the whole chain. |
| **Accessor functions (`height`, `hash`, …)** | Thin wrappers that dereference the stored pointer | No extra copying; the data is read directly from the C++ object. |
| **Registration via `caml_named_value`** | The `Break` exception is looked up once at init time | Avoids a costly name lookup on every iteration. |

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## Using the binding from OCaml

```ocaml
(* demo.ml – a tiny example program *)

(* Register the Break exception so the C stub can recognise it *)
exception Break
let () = Callback.register_exception "Blocksci.Break" Break

(* Initialise the C side (optional – it only checks that the exception was
   registered). *)
let () = Callback.register "blocksci_initialize" (fun () -> ())

(* Open the generated module (the name depends on how you compiled it). *)
let open Blocksci

let () =
  (* Simple per‑block work: count blocks whose size > 1 MiB *)
  let counter = ref 0 in
  let per_block blk =
    if size blk > 1_048_576 then incr counter;
    (* you can also do heavier work here – the loop stays in C *)
  in
  try
    iter_blocks per_block;
    Printf.printf "Large blocks: %d\n" !counter
  with
  | Break -> Printf.printf "Iteration stopped early.\n"
```

Compile & run:

```sh
dune exec ./demo.exe
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## What you have to adapt for your real project

1. **Replace the dummy BlockSci forward declarations** (`namespace blocksci { … }`)
   with the actual header(s) that define `Block`, `Chain`, and the function that
   gives you an iterator (e.g. `Chain & get_chain()` or whatever your API
   provides).

2. **Add any extra accessor you need** (e.g. transaction list, scripts, etc.).
   Each accessor is a thin wrapper that dereferences `caml_block_ptr(v_block)`.

3. **If you need parallelism** you can expose a second entry point that
   spawns a pool of worker threads in C++ and calls back into OCaml via the
   `caml_callback_exn` API (still protected by `caml_acquire_runtime_system`).

4. **Linking** – make sure the final binary links against the real BlockSci
   library (`-lblocksci` or whatever the library name is) and that the include
   path points to the BlockSci headers.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### TL;DR – the public interface you paste into *blocksci.mli*

```ocaml
type block
exception Break

val height      : block -> int
val hash        : block -> string
val timestamp   : block -> int64
val tx_count    : block -> int
val size        : block -> int

val iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit
```

…and the C++ stub *blocksci_stubs.c* (shown above) implements everything,
keeping the iteration in native code while giving OCaml users a familiar
callback‑style API similar to what pandas/Polars provide for per‑row work.
